description: From Middle English maken, from Old English macian (“to make, build, work”), from Proto-West Germanic *makōn (“to make, build, work”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂ǵ- (“to knead, mix, make”). Cognate with Latin mācerō, macer, Ancient Greek μάσσω (mássō), Scots mak (“to make”), Saterland Frisian moakje (“to make”), West Frisian meitsje (“to make”), Dutch maken (“to make”), Dutch Low Saxon maken (“to make”) and German Low German maken (“to make”), and German machen (“to make, do”). Related to match.

entries.meaning: Brand or kind; model.
examples: What make of car do you drive?

entries.meaning: Manner or style of construction (style of how a thing is made); form.
Origin (of a manufactured article); manufacture; production.
examples: The Royal Typewriter Company is distributing a very attractive eight page folder, announcing the Royal Number 10, the first machine of Royal make which uses levers instead of wires to operate the type-bars.

entries.meaning: A person's character or disposition.
(dated) The act or process of making something, especially in industrial manufacturing.
(uncountable) Quantity produced, especially of materials.
(computing) A software utility for automatically building large applications, or an implementation of this utility.
(slang) Identification or recognition (of identity), especially from police records or evidence.
(slang, usually in phrase "easy make") Past, present, or future target of seduction (usually female).
(slang, military) A promotion.
A home-made project
(card games) Turn to declare the trump for a hand (in bridge), or to shuffle the cards.
examples: 'Not your make,' said the adjutant sternly and started dealing the cards with his white be-ringed hands as though he was in haste to get rid of them.

entries.meaning: (basketball) A made basket.
(physics) The closing of an electrical circuit.

verbs.description: make (third-person singular simple present makes, present participle making, simple past and past participle made or (dialectal or obsolete) maked)

entries.meaning: To build, construct, produce, or originate.
examples: Synonyms: fabricate; see also Thesaurus:build
We made a bird feeder for our yard.
I'll make a man out of him yet.
He makes deodorants.

entries.meaning: To write or compose.
examples: I made a poem for her wedding.
He made a will.

entries.meaning: To bring about; to effect or produce by means of some action.
examples: make war
They were just a bunch of ne'er-do-wells who went around making trouble for honest men.

entries.meaning: (religious) To create (the universe), especially (in Christianity) from nothing.
examples: God made earth and heaven.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To prepare (food); to cook (food).
examples: I'm making cereal for breakfast. Who wants some?

entries.meaning: (intransitive, now mostly colloquial) To behave, to act.
examples: To make like a deer caught in the headlights.
They made nice together, as if their fight never happened.
He made as if to punch him, but they both laughed and shook hands.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To tend; to contribute; to have effect; with for or against.
examples: And all Israel's language about this power, except that it makes for righteousness, is approximate language

entries.meaning: To constitute.
examples: They make a cute couple.
This makes the third infraction.
One swallow does not a summer make.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To add up to, have a sum of.
examples: Two and four make six.

entries.meaning: (transitive, construed with of, typically interrogative) To interpret.
examples: I don’t know what to make of it.
They couldn't make anything of the inscription.
What time do you make it?

entries.meaning: (transitive, usually stressed) To bring into success.
examples: This company is what made you.
She married into wealth and so has it made.

entries.meaning: (ditransitive, second object is an adjective or participle) To cause to be.
examples: Synonym: render
The citizens made their objections clear.
This might make you a bit woozy.
Did I make myself heard?
Scotch will make you a man.

entries.meaning: To cause to appear to be; to represent as.
examples: Homer makes Aphrodite the daughter of Zeus, unlike Hesiod who depicted her as born from the sea foam.

entries.meaning: (ditransitive, second object is a verb) To cause (to do something); to compel (to do something).
examples: You're making her cry.
I was made to feel like a criminal.

entries.meaning: (ditransitive, second object is a verb, can be stressed for emphasis or clarity) To force to do.
examples: The teacher made the student study.
Don’t let them make you suffer.

entries.meaning: (ditransitive, of a fact) To indicate or suggest to be.
examples: His past mistakes don’t make him a bad person.

entries.meaning: (transitive, of a bed) To cover neatly with bedclothes.
(transitive, US slang, crime, law enforcement) To recognise, identify, spot.
examples: Synonyms: twig, notice; see also Thesaurus:identify

entries.meaning: (transitive, colloquial) To arrive at a destination, usually at or by a certain time.
examples: We should make Cincinnati by 7 tonight.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, colloquial) To proceed (in a direction).
examples: They made westward over the snowy mountains.
Make for the hills! It's a wildfire!
They made away from the fire toward the river.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To cover (a given distance) by travelling. [from 16thc.]
(transitive) To move at (a speed). [from 17thc.]
examples: The ship could make 20 knots an hour in calm seas.
This baby can make 220 miles an hour.

entries.meaning: To appoint; to name.
(transitive, slang) To induct into the Mafia or a similar organization (as a made man).
examples: Jimmy Conway: They're gonna make him.
Henry Hill: Paulie's gonna make you?

entries.meaning: (intransitive, colloquial, euphemistic) To defecate or urinate.
(transitive) To earn, to gain (money, points, membership or status).
examples: They hope to make a bigger profit.
He didn't make the choir after his voice changed.
She made ten points in that game.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To pay, to cover (an expense); chiefly used after expressions of inability.
examples: Whether, […], the construction of additional roads […] would present a case in which the exaction of prohibitory or otherwise onerous rates may be prevented, though it result in an impossibility for some or all of the roads to make expenses, we need not say; no such case is before us.

entries.meaning: (obsolete, intransitive) To compose verses; to write poetry; to versify.
examples: to solace him some time, as I do when I make

entries.meaning: To enact; to establish.
examples: Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances.

entries.meaning: To develop into; to prove to be.
examples: She'll make a fine president.

entries.meaning: To form or formulate in the mind.
examples: make plans
made a questionable decision

entries.meaning: To perform a feat.
examples: make a leap
make a pass
make a u-turn

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To gain sufficient audience to warrant its existence.
examples: In the end, my class didn't make, which left me with a bit of free time.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To act in a certain manner; to have to do; to manage; to interfere; to be active; often in the phrase to meddle or make.
(obsolete) To increase; to augment; to accrue.
(obsolete) To be engaged or concerned in.
examples: Gomez, what makest thou here, with a whole brotherhood of city bailiffs?

entries.meaning: (now archaic) To cause to be (in a specified place), used after a subjective what.
examples: Footman. Madam! Mr. Dorimant!
Lov. What makes him here?

entries.meaning: (transitive, euphemistic) To take the virginity of.
examples: I was a young un at 'Oogli,Shy as a girl to begin;Aggie de Castrer she made me,— An' Aggie was clever as sin;Older than me, but my first un —More like a mother she wereShowed me the way to promotion an' pay,An' I learned about women from 'er!

entries.meaning: (transitive) To have sexual intercourse with.
examples: Synonyms: see Thesaurus:copulate with

entries.meaning: (intransitive) Of water, to flow toward land; to rise.

description: From Middle English make, imake, from Old English ġemaca (“a mate, an equal, companion, peer”), from Proto-Germanic *gamakô (“companion, comrade”), from Proto-Indo-European *maǵ- (“to knead, oil”). Reinforced by Old Norse maki (“an equal”). Cognate with Icelandic maki (“spouse”), Swedish make (“spouse, husband”), Danish mage (“companion, fellow, mate”). See also match.

entries.meaning: (UK, dialectal) Mate; a spouse or companion; a match.
examples: Every cake hath its make; but a scrape cake hath two.

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Ireland, Northern England, now rare) A halfpenny. [from 16th c.]
examples: Only as he climbed the steps did he mind that he hadn't even a meck upon him, and turned to jump off as the tram with a showd swung grinding down to the Harbour  […]

entries.meaning: (East Anglia, Essex, obsolete) An agricultural tool resembling a scythe, used to cut (harvest) certain plants such as peas, reeds, or tares.
examples: Harvest.—When left for seed, they are cut and wadded as pease, with a make.
Produce.—From three to six sacks an acre.
